t<div id=\"contentSub\"></div>\n\t\t<div id=\"contentSub2\"></div>\n\t\t\n\t\t<div id=\"jump-to-nav\"></div>\n\t\t<a class=\"mw-jump-link\" href=\"#mw-head\">Jump to navigation</a>\n\t\t<a class=\"mw-jump-link\" href=\"#searchInput\">Jump to search</a>\n\t\t<div id=\"mw-content-text\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\" class=\"mw-content-ltr\"><div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For other people named Palladius, see <a href=\"/wiki/Palladius_(disambiguation)\" class=\"mw-redirect mw-disambig\" title=\"Palladius (disambiguation)\">Palladius (disambiguation)</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:172px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pallais_de_Saintes.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Pallais_de_Saintes.JPG/170px-Pallais_de_Saintes.JPG\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"170\" height=\"227\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Pallais_de_Saintes.JPG/255px-Pallais_de_Saintes.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Pallais_de_Saintes.JPG/340px-Pallais_de_Saintes.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"2736\" data-file-height=\"3648\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pallais_de_Saintes.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Sculpture of Palladius at the Church of <a href=\"/wiki/Saint-Palais-de-Phiolin\" title=\"Saint-Palais-de-Phiolin\">Saint-Palais-de-Phiolin</a></div></div></div>\n<p><b>Palladius</b> or more often in French <b>Pallais</b> was a 6th-century <a href=\"/wiki/Bishop_of_Saintes\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bishop of Saintes\">bishop of Saintes</a>. According to <a href=\"/wiki/Gregory_of_Tours\" title=\"Gregory of Tours\">Gregory of Tours</a>, the family of Palladius was wealthy,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and had produced several bishops and teachers throughout the 5th century in Gaul.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Palladius plotted against the <a href=\"/wiki/Merovingian_dynasty\" title=\"Merovingian dynasty\">Merovingian</a> king <a href=\"/wiki/Guntram\" title=\"Guntram\">Guntram</a>, whose territory included <a href=\"/wiki/Saintes,_Charente-Maritime\" title=\"Saintes, Charente-Maritime\">Saintes</a>, and sided with his rival <a href=\"/wiki/Gundoald\" title=\"Gundoald\">Gundoald</a>. He consecrated <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Faustianus&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Faustianus (page does not exist)\">Faustianus</a> as <a href=\"/wiki/Bishop_of_Dax\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bishop of Dax\">bishop of Dax</a> in 584, at Gundoald's behest.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> He was chastised by Guntram, who shunned having mass with him, and both the clergy under him and the <a href=\"/wiki/Metropolitan_bishop\" title=\"Metropolitan bishop\">metropolitan bishop</a> withdrew their support.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> At the <a href=\"/wiki/Second_Council_of_M%C3%A2con\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Second Council of M\u00e2con\">Second Council of M\u00e2con</a> in 585, the assembled bishops agreed to depose Faustianus, and fined Palladius and two other prelates an annual amount to support him. Two years later, Palladius plotted with <a href=\"/wiki/Fredegund\" title=\"Fredegund\">Fredegund</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Palladius worked effectively toward building churches and obtaining <a href=\"/wiki/Relic\" title=\"Relic\">relics</a> for his <a href=\"/wiki/Diocese\" title=\"Diocese\">diocese</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> He procured relics of <a href=\"/wiki/Martin_of_Tours\" title=\"Martin of Tours\">Martin of Tours</a>, built a church in his honor, and reported several healing miracles to have occurred within the first two or three months.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> Palladius also promoted <a href=\"/wiki/Cult_of_saints\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cult of saints\">saints' cults</a> for Eutropius, the first bishop of Saintes, and for the Abbot Martinus who may have studied with Martin of Tours.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 573, Palladius was a signatory to the <a href=\"/wiki/Canon_law_(Catholic_Church)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Canon law (Catholic Church)\">canons</a> of the <a href=\"/wiki/Fourth_Council_of_Paris\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Fourth Council of Paris\">Fourth Council of Paris</a>, and hosted a council within his own diocese in 573. He is last mentioned in 595.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Palladius_of_Saintes&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Gregory of Tours, <i>De Gloria Confessorum</i> 40; Bennett, <i>DCBLSD<sup>4</sup></i>, p. 177.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Raymond van Dam, <i>Saints and Their Miracles in Late Antique Gaul</i> (Princeton University Press, 1993), p. 288.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Gregory, <i>History of the Franks</i> 7.31, 8.2; Bennett, <i>DCBLSD<sup>4</sup></i>, p. 177.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Van Dam, <i>Saints and Their Miracles,</i> p. 288.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Bennett, <i>DCBLSD<sup>4</sup></i>, p. 177.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Bennett, <i>DCBLSD<sup>4</sup></i>, p. 177.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Van Dam, <i>Saints and Their Miracles,</i> p. 288.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Van Dam, <i>Saints and Their Miracles,</i> p. 288.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Bennett, <i>DCBLSD<sup>4</sup></i>, p. 177.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1403\nCached time: 20200813191150\nCache expiry: 2592000\nDynamic content: false\nComplications: []\nCPU time usage: 0.080 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.128 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 200/1000000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 614/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 84/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 8/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 2626/5000000 bytes\nLua time usage: 0.032/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1